WEBVTT

00:00.792 --> 00:06.179
Hello everyone! Welcome back to another episode of the Grand Prixquel Podcast, where we discuss all things feeder series.

00:06.519 --> 00:10.584
On today's episode, we are going to be doing a Eurocup 3 season preview.

00:11.405 --> 00:14.730
Today's hosts are myself, Robin, Alex and Peter.

00:18.920 --> 00:29.286
The Eurocup 3 is a regional series similar to FRECA or GB3, in between F4 and F3 and it is the parent series to Spanish F4 also.

00:29.647 --> 00:35.570
We see a lot of drivers from Spanish F4 then move up to Eurocup 3 or EC3 for short.

00:36.070 --> 00:42.474
And we’ve also recently, we had the winter series which we just talked about in an earlier episode as well.

00:42.935 --> 00:45.676
We have a new car for this year, the Dallara 326.

00:47.538 --> 00:49.802
Way better than whatever FREC has going on.

00:50.783 --> 00:53.784
It was very exciting racing in the winter series.

00:53.804 --> 00:56.305
Highly recommend you go watch it if you've not.

00:56.846 --> 00:58.066
All available on YouTube.

00:58.746 --> 01:06.890
But there is a bit of confusion over the new car, I think, because it was meant to not have push to pass, but in the winter series it had push to pass.

01:07.610 --> 01:11.352
So, I guess we need to just see in the main series what happens.

01:11.652 --> 01:14.213
But, overall, it's very enjoyable racing.

01:14.773 --> 01:19.375
And in terms of the calendar, it’s pretty- quite similar to FREC.

01:19.815 --> 01:32.158
Because again, regional, Formula Regional series, we have Silverstone, Hungaroring, Barcelona and Monza, to name a few, and potentially the new Madrid ring, which we're also seeing in Formula One.

01:32.859 --> 01:40.781
I think that's just not been officially announced as it needs to be officially homologated or, but fairly sure it's going to be there.

01:41.665 --> 01:50.728
Wasn't there like, a whole, like, discussion where the Madring guys posted “no, like we don't have, we don't host another thing”?

01:50.788 --> 01:52.149
It was like a whole thing.

01:52.189 --> 01:54.250
So we really don't know.

01:54.410 --> 01:57.451
I read the, um, what's it called?

01:58.091 --> 01:59.071
The regulations.

02:00.132 --> 02:03.333
Um, and I'm pretty sure it says the Madring there, I think.

02:03.748 --> 02:05.005
Great.

02:05.005 --> 02:28.622
We just have to wait and see. I mean, it could be fun to see these cars on a street circuit because you've seen them race incredibly well. And also for the drivers, when you move up to F3 and F2, you do have more street circuits so that would be a good experience for them as well. And over the course of- we have three races over a weekend, which includes the sprint race.

02:29.993 --> 02:42.507
And it's basically a fairly standard points for a feeder series with 25 for the winner, 18 for second and so on, with also 2 for pole and 1 for fastest lap.

02:43.308 --> 02:46.151
All fairly standard if you're familiar with the feeder series.

02:47.573 --> 02:54.539
I didn’t hear if you mentioned this bit, but the sprint race format is only there for three weekends.

02:54.599 --> 03:00.164
It's not there for the entire championship, unlike the Spanish Winter Championship which had it for all three rounds.

03:01.318 --> 03:11.420
It's very much similar to FREC, then, in the sense that... Yeah, except unlike FREC, we actually know which circuits the sprint races are going to be on.

03:12.201 --> 03:22.263
In the regs, it says three tracks–even though on the wiki for some reason it says four–but the regs say Paul Ricard, Imola, and Silverstone will have the sprint races.

03:23.037 --> 03:26.419
Good choice of track, especially Silverstone, it's going to be a fun race.

03:27.920 --> 03:31.343
And we also have the team's title in Eurocup 3.

03:31.943 --> 03:34.685
